To find the projection of vector $\mathbf{a}$ onto vector $\mathbf{b}$, we use the formula:
\[
\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}} \mathbf{a} = \frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{b}} \mathbf{b}
\]
where $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$. Let's first find the dot products $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{b}$. 

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} &= (1)(8) + (-2)(1) \\
&= 8 - 2 \\
&= 6.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{b} &= (8)(8) + (1)(1) \\
&= 64 + 1 \\
&= 65.
\end{align*}

Now, we can find the projection vector:
$$
\text{proj}_{\mathbf{b}} \mathbf{a} = \frac{6}{65} \begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{6}{65} \times 8 \\ \frac{6}{65} \times 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{48}{65} \\ \frac{6}{65} \end{pmatrix}
$$</think> <answer> $\begin{pmatrix} \frac{48}{65} \\ \frac{6}{65} \end{pmatrix}$ </answer>

