Then $\angle BQP = 180^\circ - 2x,$ and $\angle PQA = 2x.$  Since triangle $APQ$ is isosceles, $\angle QAP = 2x.$  Then $\angle APQ = 180^\circ - 4x,$ so $\angle QPC = 4x.$  Since $\angle QPB = x,$ $\angle BPC = 3x.$

Also, since triangle $ABC$ is isosceles,
\[\angle ABC = \angle ACB = \frac{180^\circ - \angle BAC}{2} = 90^\circ - x.\]By the Law of Sines on triangle $BCP,$
\[\frac{BC}{BP} = \frac{\sin 3x}{\sin (90^\circ - x)} = \frac{\sin 3x}{\cos x}.\]By the Law of Sines on triangle $PQB,$
\[\frac{PQ}{BP} = \frac{\sin x}{\sin 2x} = \frac{\sin x}{2 \sin x \cos x} = \frac{1}{2 \cos x}.\]Since $BC = PQ,$ $\frac{\sin 3x}{\cos x} = \frac{1}{2 \cos x},$ so
\[\sin 3x = \frac{1}{2}.\]Since $\angle APQ = 180^\circ - 4x,$ $x < \frac{180^\circ}{4} = 45^\circ,$ so $3x < 135^\circ.$  Therefore, $3x = 30^\circ,$ so $x = 10^\circ.$

Then $\angle ACB = 90^\circ - x = 80^\circ$ and $\angle APQ = 140^\circ,$ and the ratio we seek is $\frac{80}{140} = \boxed{\frac{4}{7}}.$

